Rig. by con- ject. reads qui for quam qui, ex- plaining it by saying that sometimes when the beasts were let in, one gladiator to save himself thrust another forward, who if successful against the lion sometimes fought with the first gladiator and was slain by him, who was thus twice a murderer. This is approved by Oehler, but seems to me forced. The reading of the MSS. quam qui is adopted by La Cerda, who con- ceives qui juqulat to be the lion. But there is little probability in this.
